`,d.jsx(r.p,{children:"Before building a Redis server that stores a key, expires a value, or replicates a write, we need to choose a language it should understand from the client. The understanding begins at the wire protocol."}),`
`,d.jsxs(r.p,{children:["Since we wanted this to be Redis compatible, we will choose the same protocol that Redis uses to communicate, called RESP: Redis Serialization Protocol. It is a complete specification for how bytes transfer between a client and server. Every command that you call, ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"GET"}),", ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"SET"}),", ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"EXPIRE"}),", passes through RESP on its way in and out."]}),`
`,d.jsxs(r.p,{children:["Most of you using Redis might never need to know about this, but since I am building a Redis-compatible server that must correctly handle ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"redis-cli"}),", ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"Jedis"}),", ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"Lettuce"}),", and ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"redis-py"})," without any modification, RESP is something I need to get right. Everything else in the server is downstream of the parser."]}),`
`,d.jsx(r.p,{children:"This article covers what RESP looks like, why it is designed the way it is, and the specific challenges of parsing it correctly in a high-throughput streaming context."}),`
`,d.jsx(r.h2,{children:"Why not JSON? Why not HTTP?"}),`
`,d.jsx(r.p,{children:"This is a valid question. Redis was designed in 2009 and JSON was already well established while HTTP was present everywhere. Why was there a need to invent a completely new protocol at all?"}),`
`,d.jsx(r.p,{children:"The answer is simple: neither JSON nor HTTP is well-suited to the access pattern of a key-value store. JSON is a text format designed for human readability and schema flexibility. Both of these properties do not matter in a cache protocol. You do not need human-readable bytes. You do not need nested schemas. What you actually need is a format that is extremely fast to parse, produces low overhead per command, and maps directly to a small set of response types that a server typically returns: string, integer, error, list of strings, or nothing."}),`
`,d.jsxs(r.p,{children:["HTTP carries a significant framing overhead. Every request includes a method, path, headers, and a body separator. For a workload where the average command is ",d.jsx(r.code,{children:"GET key"}),", around 10 bytes of meaningful content, the HTTP headers actually dwarf the actual payload. HTTP is also inherently request-response, one at a time per connection, which conflicts directly with pipelining."]}),`
`,d.jsx(r.p,{children:"RESP makes the opposite tradeoffs. It is binary-safe, minimal, and streaming friendly. A GET command is expressed in around 20 bytes. A bulk string response carries its length prefix rather than a delimiter, which means the parser never has to scan the entire content. It can skip directly to the end because it already knows the end location from the prefix length. All design decisions in RESP optimize for the throughput and simplicity of a command response protocol over a persistent connection."}),`
`,d.jsxs(r.table,{children:[d.jsx(r.thead,{children:d.jsxs(r.tr,{children:[d.jsx(r.th,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"Protocol"}),d.jsx(r.th,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"Avg overhead"}),d.jsx(r.th,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"Parsing cost"}),d.jsx(r.th,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"Binary-safe"}),d.jsx(r.th,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"Pipelining"})]})}),d.jsxs(r.tbody,{children:[d.jsxs(r.tr,{children:[d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:d.jsx(r.strong,{children:"RESP"})}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"~20 bytes"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"O(1) type byte"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"✓"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"✓"})]}),d.jsxs(r.tr,{children:[d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"HTTP/1.1"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"~400+ bytes"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"O(n) header scan"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"✗"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"Limited"})]}),d.jsxs(r.tr,{children:[d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"JSON"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"Variable"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"O(n) full parse"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"✗"}),d.jsx(r.td,{style:{textAlign:"left"},children:"✗"})]})]})]}),`
`,d.jsx(a,{type:"tip",title:"The design insight",children:d.jsx(r.p,{children:"A bulk string response carries its length prefix rather than a delimiter. The parser reads a declared byte count and jumps directly to the end. It never scans the content at all. That single property is what makes RESP both binary-safe and stream-friendly at the same time."})}),`
`,d.jsx(r.hr,{}),`
